ğŸ”¹ 1ï¸âƒ£ What does â€œcall a classâ€ mean?
ğŸ‘‰ We do NOT call a class directly
ğŸ‘‰ We create an OBJECT of the class and then use that object

Rule:
Class â†’ create Object â†’ use methods/variables

ğŸ”¹ 2ï¸âƒ£ How to create an OBJECT?
General syntax:
ClassName objectName = new ClassName();

ğŸ”¹ 3ï¸âƒ£ Simple example (NORMAL CLASS)
class Student {
    int id = 101;
    void study() {
        System.out.println("Student is studying");
    }
}

Using this class in main()
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student();   // object creation
        System.out.println(s.id);    // accessing variable
        s.study();                   // calling method
    }
}

Output:
101
Student is studying

ğŸ“Œ Explanation

Student â†’ class
s â†’ object
. (dot) â†’ used to access members

ğŸ”¹ 4ï¸âƒ£ Object used for WHAT?

An object is used to:

Access variables
Call methods
Store data
Perform actions

ğŸ”¹ 5ï¸âƒ£ Calling different TYPES of classes (IMPORTANT â­)
ğŸ”¸ A) Calling a NORMAL class
Animal a = new Animal();

ğŸ”¸ B) Calling a class with METHODS
class Calculator {
    void add() {
        System.out.println(10 + 20);
    }
}
Calculator c = new Calculator();
c.add();

ğŸ”¸ C) Calling a STATIC method (NO object)
class Demo {
    static void show() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
}
Demo.show();   // No object needed

ğŸ“Œ static belongs to class, not object

ğŸ”¹ 6ï¸âƒ£ Calling INNER CLASSES (from your code)
ğŸ”¸ A) Normal Inner Class
Outer outer = new Outer();
Outer.Inner inner = outer.new Inner();

ğŸ”¸ B) Static Nested Class
Outer.Nested nested = new Outer.Nested();

ğŸ”¸ C) Local Inner Class
outer.localClass();   // only inside method

ğŸ”¸ D) Anonymous Inner Class
Animal a = new Animal() {
};

ğŸ“Œ No class name, object created directly

ğŸ”¹ 7ï¸âƒ£ Why we NEED objects?

ğŸ‘‰ Because non-static members need an object
Example:
class Demo {
    int x = 10;
    void show() {
        System.out.println(x);
    }
}

âŒ This is wrong:
